y beginning in the second century BC.  The first to obtain the [[Roman consul|consul]]ship was [[Publius Rutilius Rufus]] in 105 BC.<ref name=\"DGRBM Rutilia Gens\">''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. III, pp. 680, 681 (\"Rutilia Gens\").</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe [[Roman naming conventions#Nomen|nomen]] ''Rutilius'' is derived from the [[Latin]] [[cognomen]] ''Rutilus'', red or reddish, which was probably borne by an ancestor of the family who had red hair.  The nomen belongs to a large class of gentilicia derived from other names using the suffix ''{{not a typo|-ilius}}''.<ref>Chase, pp. 110, 122, 123.</ref>\n\n==Praenomina==\nThe Rutilii used relatively few [[praenomen|praenomina]], chiefly ''[[Publius (praenomen)|Publius]]'', ''[[Lucius (praenomen)|Lucius]]'', ''[[Marcus (praenomen)|Marcus]]'', and ''[[Gaius (praenomen)|Gaius]]'', all of which were among the most common names throughout Roman history.  The only other praenomen found under the [[Roman Republic|Republic]] was ''[[Quintus (praenomen)|Quintus]]'', known from Quintus Rutilius, [[quaestor]] in 44 BC.\n\n==Branches and cognomina==\nThe Rutilii of the Republic bore the [[cognomen|cognomina]] ''Calvus'', ''Lupus'' and ''[[Rufus (Roman cognomen)|Rufus]]''.  In addition to these, the coins of the Rutilii include the surname ''[[Flaccus]]'', which does not occur in literary sources.  Other cognomina occur in the [[Roman Empire|imperial times]].  A number of Rutilii bore no surname.<ref name=\"DGRBM Rutilia Gens\"/>  ''Rufus'', red, was typically given to someone with red hair, and this choice of cognomen may have been influenced by the fact that the nomen ''Rutilius'' has the same meaning.<ref name=\"Chase 109 110\">Chase, pp. 109, 110.</ref>  Another of the surnames of the Rutilii, ''Calvus'', indicated someone bald, while ''Lupus'', a wolf, belongs to a common type of cognomen derived from familiar objects and animals.<ref name=\"Chase 109 110\"/><ref>Chase, pp. 112, 113.</ref><ref>''New College Latin & English Dictionary'', ''s. v. Lupus''.</ref>  ''Flaccus'' indicated someone flabby, or with floppy ears.<ref name=\"Chase 109 110\"/><ref>''New College Latin & English Dictionary'', ''s. v. Flaccus''.</ref>\n\n==Members==\n{{Filiation}}\n\n* Spurius Rutilius Crassus, according to [[Livy]], one of the [[tribuni militum consulari potestate|consular tribunes]] in 417 BC, is probably a mistake for Spurius Veturius Crassus, named by [[Diodorus Siculus]], since no other Rutilii are mentioned for over two and a half centuries.<ref>Livy, iv. 47.</ref><ref>Diodorus Siculus, xiii. 7.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. I, p. 73.</ref>\n\n===Rutilii Rufi===\n* Publius Rutilius (Rufus?), [[Tribune of the Plebs|tribune of the plebs]] in 169 BC, opposed the actions of the [[Roman censor|censors]] with regard to the [[publican|publicani]] and one of his own [[patronage in ancient Rome|clients]], and brought them to trial, in retaliation for which they removed him from his [[Roman tribe|tribe]], and degraded him to the status of an [[aerarii|aerarius]].<ref>Livy, xiii. 16, xiv. 44.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. I, pp. 425, 427 (note 3).</ref>\n* [[Publius Rutilius Rufus|Publius Rutilius P. f. Rufus]], had served as a [[military tribune]] under [[Scipio Aemilianus]] in [[Numantine War|Spain]], [[praetor]] ''circa'' 118, and as consul in 105 took emergency measures to protect Rome following a series of military disasters in [[Gaul]].  He was falsely exiled for ''repetundae'' in 92.  Rufus was an ally of [[Gaius Marius]], granduncle of [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]].<ref>Cicero, ''Pro Fonteio'', 13, ''Brutus'', 30, ''Pro Balbo'', 11.</ref><ref>Livy, ''Epitome'', lxx.</ref><ref>Velleius Paterculus, ii. 13.</ref><ref>Valerius Maximus, ii. 10. \u00a7 5.</ref><ref>Seneca the Younger, ''De Beneficiis'', vi. 37.</ref><ref>Ovid, ''Epistulae ex Ponto'', i. 3, 63.</ref><ref>Suetonius, ''De Illustribus Grammaticis'', 6.</ref><ref>Orosius, v. 17.</ref><ref>''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. III, pp. 681, 682 (\"Publius Rutilius Rufus\").</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. I, pp. 491, 494, 527, 528 (note 1), 536, 537 (note 5), 547, 549, 552, 555, vol. II, pp. 8, 9 (note 6).</ref>\n* Gaius Rutilius (P. f.) Rufus, a friend of [[Quintus Mucius Scaevola Augur|Quintus Mucius Scaevola]], was one of those who accused [[Manius Aquillius (consul 129 BC)|Manius Aquillius]], the consul of 129 BC, of ''repetundae'', or extortion in the government of his province.<ref>Cicero, ''Divinatio in Caecilium'', 21, ''Brutus'', 40.</ref>\n* Rutilia P. f., wife of Marcus Aurelius Cotta, and later Lucius Aurelius Cotta.  By Marcus, she was the mother of [[Gaius Aurelius Cotta]], the orator.  By Lucius, she was the mother of [[Aurelia Cotta|Aurelia]], the mother of [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]].<ref>Seneca, ''Consolatio ad Helviam'', 16.</ref><ref>Cicero, ''Epistulae ad Atticum'', xii. 20, 22.</ref>\n\n===Rutilii Lupi===\n* [[Publius Rutilius Lupus (consul)|Publius Rutilius L. f. L. n. Lupus]], consul in 90 BC, at the beginning of the [[Social War (91\u201388 BC)|Social War]], appointed Marius as his legate, but through lack of experience led his men into an ambush, and was mortally wounded.<ref>Appian, ''Bellum Civile'', i. 40, 43.</ref><ref>Orosius, v. 18.</ref><ref>Velleius Paterculus, ii. 15, 16.</ref><ref>Livy, ''Epitome'', 73.</ref><ref>Pliny the Elder, ii. 29. s. 30.</ref><ref>Florus, iii. 18.</ref><ref>Obsequens, 115.</ref><ref>Cicero, ''Pro Fonteio'', 15.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. II, pp. 15, 25</ref>\n* Publius Rutilius (P. f. L. n.) Lupus, tribune of the plebs in 56 BC, proposed repealing Caesar's agrarian law.  Praetor 49, at the beginning of the [[Caesar's Civil War|Civil War]], he was a partisan of [[Pompey|Pompeius]], and stationed at [[Terracina|Tarracina]], but departed before Caesar's arrival, returning to Rome.  In 48, Pompeius appointed him governor of [[Achaea (Roman province)|Achaia]].<ref>Cicero, ''Epistulae ad Quintum Fratrem'', ii. 1, ''Epistulae ad Familiares'', i. 1, 2, ''Epistulae ad Atticum'', viii. 12, A. \u00a7 4, ix. 1. \u00a7 2.</ref><ref>Caesar, ''De Bello Civili'', i. 24, iii. 55.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. II, pp. 209, 258, 278.</ref>\n* [[Publius Rutilius Lupus (rhetorician)|Publius Rutilius (P. f. P. n.) Lupus]], a grammarian and rhetorician, active during the reign of [[Tiberius]].  He was the author of ''De Figuris Sententiarum et Elocutionis'', a collection of translated passages from Greek authors, many of which are no longer extant in the original.<ref>''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. II, p. 841 (\"Rutilius Lupus\").</ref>\n* [[Marcus Rutilius Lupus]], prefect of Egypt from AD 113 to 117, during [[Kitos War|a revolt]] in [[Alexandria]] and [[Hermopolis]].\n\n=== Others ===\n* Publius Rutilius Calvus, praetor in 166 BC, probably received the province of [[Hispania Ulterior]].  Some scholars identify him with the tribune degraded in 169, but M\u00fcnzer suggests that the tribune was one of the Rutilii Rufi.<ref>Livy, xlv. 44.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. I, p. 427 (note 3), 437 (and note 1).</ref>\n* Publius Rutilius M. f., tribune of the plebs in 136 BC, ordered [[Gaius Hostilius Mancinus]] to vacate his seat in the [[Roman Senate|senate]], on the grounds that his [[Roman citizenship]] had been revoked when the senate handed him over to the [[Numantine War|Numantines]] following his defeat the previous year.<ref>Cicero, ''De Oratore'', i. 40.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. I, p. 487.</ref>\n* Rutilius, one of [[Sulla|Sulla's]] officers, whom he sent to [[Gaius Flavius Fimbria]] in 84 BC.<ref>Appian, ''Bella Mithridatica'', 60.</ref>\n* Gaius Rutilius, mentioned by [[Cicero]] as one who had been accused by a certain Gaius Rucius, should perhaps be read ''Hirtilius''.<ref>Cicero, ''Brutus'', 74.</ref>\n* Lucius Rutilius Flaccus, ''[[List of Roman moneyers during the Republic|triumvir monetalis]]'' around 75 BC, and a [[Roman Senate|senator]] in 72.\n* {{Publius Rutilius Nudus|ru|\u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u0443\u0434}}, a [[legatus|legate]] serving under the consul [[Marcus Aurelius Cotta (consul 74 BC)|Marcus Aurelius Cotta]] at [[Chalcedon]] in 74 BC.<ref>Appian, ''Bella Mithridatica'', 71.</ref><ref>Orosius, vi. 2.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. II, p. 105.</ref>\n* Publius Rutilius, a witness named by Cicero in support of [[Aulus Caecina Severus (writer)|Aulus Caecina]], whom he defended in his oration, ''[[Pro Caecina]]'', in 69 BC.<ref>Cicero, ''Pro Caecina'', 10.</ref>\n* Marcus Rutilius, placed in charge of distributing land to Caesar's soldiers in 45 BC.<ref>Cicero, ''Epistulae ad Familiares'', xiii. 8.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. II, p. 313.</ref>\n* Quintus Rutilius, [[quaestor]] ''urbanus'' in 44 BC.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquitates Juda\u00efcae'', xiv. 219.</ref><ref>Broughton, vol. II, p. 326.</ref>\n* [[Gaius Rutilius Gallicus]], ''[[praefectus urbi]]'' during the reign of [[Domitian]].<ref>Juvenal, xiii. 157.</ref><ref>Statius, ''Silvae'', i. 4.</ref>\n* Rutilius Geminus, author of a tragedy entitled ''[[Astyanax]]''.  [[Fabius Planciades Fulgentius|Fulgentius]] connects him with the ''[[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#libri pontificales|Libri Pontificales]]''.<ref>Fulgentius, ''Expositio Sermonum Antiquorum'', 7.</ref><ref>Bothe, ''Po\u00ebtae Scenici Latinorum'', p. 270.</ref><ref>Boyle, ''An Introduction to Roman Tragedy'', p. 277.</ref>\n* Rutilius Maximus, a jurist, and the author of ''Ad Legem Falcidiam'', a treatise on a law enacted in 40 BC by [[Publius Falcidius]], tribune of the plebs, requiring that the heir of an estate had to take at least one quarter of the property in question.<ref>Digesta, 30. s. 125.</ref>\n* Claudius Rutilius Numatianus, ''praefectus urbi'' ''circa'' AD 413 or 414, was a native of Gaul, and the author of an elegy known as the ''Itinerarium'', or ''De Reditu'', in two books, composed about 417.  He was a pagan, and his writing shows some hostility to Jewish and Christian practices.<ref>Wernsdorf, ''Po\u00ebtae Latini Minores'', vols. ii, v, part 1, ''prolegomena''.</ref>\n* [[Rutilius Taurus Aemilianus Palladius]], the author of ''De Re Rustica'', a treatise on agriculture, perhaps dating to the fifth century.<ref>''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. III, pp. 99, 100 (\"Rutilius Taurus Aemilianus Palladius\").</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Roman gentes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]], ''[[Brutus (Cicero)|Brutus]]'', ''[[De Oratore]]'', ''[[Divinatio in Caecilium|Divinatio in Quintum Caecilium]]'', ''[[Epistulae ad Atticum]]'', ''[[Epistulae ad Familiares]]'', ''[[Epistulae ad Quintum Fratrem]]'', ''Pro Balbo'', ''[[Pro Caecina]]'', ''Pro Fonteio''.\n* [[Julius Caesar|Gaius Julius Caesar]], ''[[Commentarii de Bello Civili]]'' (Commentaries on the Civil War).\n* [[Diodorus Siculus]], ''[[Bibliotheca historica|Bibliotheca Historica]]'' (Library of History).\n* Titus Livius ([[Livy]]), ''[[Ab Urbe Condita Libri (Livy)|History of Rome]]''.\n* Publius Ovidius Naso ([[Ovid]]), ''[[Epistulae ex Ponto]]'' (Letters from Pontus).\n* [[Marcus Velleius Paterculus]], ''Compendium of Roman History''.\n* [[Valerius Maximus]], ''[[Factorum ac dictorum memorabilium libri IX|Factorum ac Dictorum Memorabilium]]'' (Memorable Facts and Sayings).\n* Lucius Annaeus Seneca ([[Seneca the Younger]]), ''De Beneficiis'' (On Kindness), ''[[Seneca's Consolations|De Consolatione Ad Helviam]]'' (To Helvia, on Consolation).\n* Gaius Plinius Secundus ([[Pliny the Elder]]), ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Historia Naturalis]]'' (Natural History).\n* [[Statius|Publius Papinius Statius]], ''Silvae''.\n* [[Juvenal|Decimus Junius Juvenalis]], ''[[Satires of Juvenal|Satirae]]'' (Satires).\n* [[Josephus|Flavius Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquitates Juda\u00efcae]]'' (Antiquities of the Jews).\n* [[Suetonius|Gaius Suetonius T